      <title>Reconciliation Bill to be Signed on July 4</title>
      <author>Amy West       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/518/2025-07-03_reconciliation-bill-to-be-signed-on-july-4</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/518/2025-07-03_reconciliation-bill-to-be-signed-on-july-4</guid>
      <pubDate>Thu, 03 Jul 2025 17:42:28 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;After modifications in the Senate to win over Sen. Murkowski (R-AK) and the removal of a few provisions deemed invalid by the the Parliamentarian, the Senate passed their version of &lt;a href="https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/119/hr1/text"&gt;H.R. 1: To provide for reconciliation pursuant to title II of H. Con. Res. 14&lt;/a&gt; on Tuesday, July 1st. One of the revisions was to change the bill's name, reflected here.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The House passed it on July 3 unchanged from the Senate's version by &lt;a href="https://bsky.app/profile/jamiedupree.bsky.social/post/3lt3ejs26ts2a"&gt;218-214&lt;/a&gt;. The President will sign it tomorrow, July 4.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;What's in the Bill?&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;The reconciliation bill is &lt;a href="https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2025/06/30/upshot/senate-republican-megabill.html?unlocked_article_code=1.Tk8.QdEi.oia9tReDLQFk&amp;amp;smid=url-share"&gt;primarily permanent tax breaks&lt;/a&gt;, estimated to cost nearly $5 trillion dollars. The better off you are, the more benefit you'll see from the bill. The poorer you are, the more it will penalize you. The &lt;a href="https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2025/06/30/upshot/senate-republican-megabill.html"&gt;bill makes up for the tax breaks&lt;/a&gt; by making Medicaid harder to get, making states pay for more of it, limiting how states can raise funds to pay for their portion, cutting who can get SNAP benefits and reducing the benefits for those who get them. It also makes cuts in student loan programs and cuts funding and tax credits for green energy, &lt;a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2025/07/02/biden-trump-climate-republicans-bill/"&gt;including manufacturing in a host of majority Republican states&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The reconciliation bill appropriates &lt;a href="https://boltsmag.org/how-the-gop-megabill-would-turbocharge-local-immigration-enforcement/"&gt;$171 billion dollars&lt;/a&gt; overall for immigration related activities. This would make &lt;a href="https://www.democracynow.org/2025/7/2/trump_budget_bill_ice_immigration_enforcement"&gt;ICE the largest law enforcement agency&lt;/a&gt; in the United States.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The bill is &lt;a href="https://substack.perfectunion.us/p/the-one-big-beautiful-bill-is-a-big?r=bqby&amp;amp;utm_campaign=post&amp;amp;utm_medium=web"&gt;a jackpot for a host of industries&lt;/a&gt; including pharmaceutical companies, oil and gas drillers, private space companies, defense manufacturers, private prison companies (who also operate ICE detention facilities), gun and silencer manufacturers and investment firms.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2025/06/28/us/politics/republicans-alaska-murkowski-bill.html"&gt;In order to secure a vote in favor from Sen. Murkowski (R-AK)&lt;/a&gt;, Alaska was exempted from the new Medicaid and SNAP requirements other states will have to meet and a tax credit for whaling for subsistence purposes by indigenous Alaskans was expanded.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;What's not in the Bill?&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;In the Senate negotiations, provisions for the &lt;a href="https://www.cbsnews.com/news/sen-mike-lee-removes-public-lands-provision-from-trumps-big-beautiful-bill/"&gt;sale of public lands&lt;/a&gt; were removed, as were provisions &lt;a href="https://www.lgbtqnation.com/2025/07/senate-drops-anti-trans-provisions-to-barely-pass-major-budget-bill-that-cuts-medicaid/"&gt;banning care for transgender people&lt;/a&gt;. You can see the other few provisions removed in this &lt;a href="https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2025/06/30/upshot/senate-republican-megabill.html?unlocked_article_code=1.Tk8.QdEi.oia9tReDLQFk&amp;amp;smid=url-share"&gt;New York Times article&lt;/a&gt;; look for the red highlights.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h2&gt;What's next?&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;Probably not much for a while. Traditionally both chambers recess for all of August so when they return next week, there'll probably be a few bills passed in the House and a few more confirmations in the Senate in July.&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
